label: Baptisms, Burials, Confirmations and Marriages - 16th & 17th Centuries
description: Box 2 - Baptisms, Burials, Confirmations and Marriages contains records created in Florida during the early-seventeenth century. All records in Box 2 contain information on indios, negros, and espa√±oles. There is a single confirmation folio dated as 1509 and contains entries from Pueblo de San Francisco and an unknown pueblo. Almost certainly, these pueblos were not in Florida. The baptismal records range from 10 January 1617 to 9 June 1633. They comprise two separate folio pagination ranges (42r-80r and 126r-[130]v), but without any noticeable missing entries and with each year accounted for. At a minimum, each baptismal entry provides name of individual; date of baptism; if known, parents' names; if anyone is a slave, owner's name; name/s of godparent/s (padrino/s); legitimacy of birth; and name and title of priest who performed the baptism. The burial records range from 6 January 1632 to 15 October 1638 and comprise nine folios, beginning with folio 150r. At a minimum, each burial entry provides the date of burial; the name and title of presiding priest; place of burial (e.g., convent of San Francisco, hospital, church); individual's name or if individual was too young to have recieved a name, then a parent's name; and if individual is a slave.  Additional information includes, but is not limited to, the following: spouse's name; occupation (e.g., marinero); if slave, owner's name. The confirmations are from 1606 and comprise folios 108r-117v. The confirmation records provide the individual's name; race, color and/or slave status; and padrino's name. The marriage records range from 17 June 1616 to 28 November 1631 and comprise folios 97r-107v. There is an extra marriage folio that contains entries from 19 January 1619 to 3 March 1620, and it is numbered as folio 100. At a minimum, each marriage entry includes the date of the marriage; names of the bride and groom; name and title of priest who performed the marriage; and if not white, then the racial designation, skin color, or slave status of the bridge, groom, and/or godparent/s (padrino/s). Additional information includes, but is not limited to, the following: time of day the marriage occured, place the marriage took place (e.g., hospital), military rank and/or administrative title of any male named in the entry.
